Europe needs to restart its immigration process
Brussels—over 900 migrants who attempted to reach Europe have drowned in the Mediterranean this year.
At the same time, rescue ships Open Arms and Ocean Viking have been searching for a safe port to allow passengers on board to disembark throughout the summer.
The refugee and migrant camps on the Greek island of Lesbos are overcrowded, and the conditions in other Libyan detention camps are similar.
Turkey has torn up the 2016 agreement that blocked migrants from entering the EU.
Despite Europe's desire to help migrants and respect international law, it does not want its camps to be overcrowded.
The number of refugees and migrants entering the EU surged in 2015-16 - many were fleeing the Syrian conflict - which had a huge impact on trust within the EU.
The massive influx of migrants eroded confidence in governments' ability to manage external borders and asylum, and highlighted the futility of cooperation with migrant source countries.
Thus, migration became a political football, a tasty treat for populists.
Under the leadership of President von der Leyen, the new European Commission must regain control of migration issues while respecting the dignity of those seeking a better life.
The EU needs to redefine its policies on four aspects to mobilize member states for European interests.
Firstly, the EU must urgently ensure the security of its external borders, which is a prerequisite for keeping internal borders open.
Any people who can freely move within a country, including the United States, India, China, Switzerland, and Russia, will not outsource control of their external borders to a state or region.
Controlling the EU's external borders must be a collective task and a national task.
The European Border and Coast Guard Agency (Frontex) must be further strengthened, and it should be deployed with joint patrols by member states — including coastlines and airports.
The EU must also restart Operation Sophia to combat Mediterranean illegal immigration.
Secondly, Europe needs to handle economic migrants and asylum seekers separately.
Mixing them up has already brought the asylum system to the brink of collapse; handling them separately would help ensure that migrants who fear for their lives can voice their concerns while having their rights protected.
Solving the EU's real economic and social needs requires effective blue or green card policies for economic migrants and implementing overall migration targets.
This cannot wait for the next migration crisis to consider introducing these mechanisms.
To achieve this, the EU must break the taboo.
Firstly, the number of economically migrant workers entering the EU labor market must be recognized as a common interest issue.
Secondly, policies must clearly define which immigrants are welcome.
Thirdly, member states must answer which EU help is needed to achieve a smooth migration process.
Finally, visas and work permits must be brought to the forefront to facilitate the return of illegal migrants to their countries of origin.
Indeed, according to the EU treaty, each member state needs to manage its own immigration from outside the EU.
However, if governments reach an agreement on a general EU migration target, it would be a significant step forward.
In turn, member states can specify the desired economic migrant source countries and requirements, as well as the EU budget resources needed to accommodate them.
This way, migration acceptance would become a privilege rather than a burden.
For example, Canada has already established an active immigration policy, selecting migrants based on indicators such as source country, skills, and age range.
Europe can do the same.
Thirdly, the EU needs to improve its asylum system.
Firstly, the strict requirement of mandatory distribution of asylum seekers within the EU must be abolished.
This requirement has destroyed the atmosphere within the EU, but if the border, asylum, and migration systems are fully effective, it may still be feasible.
Furthermore, it cannot be expected that the EU's frontline member states can single-handedly solve the problem of illegal migrants crossing the external borders.
Reception centers are overcrowded, migrants are subjected to abuse by authorities, or forced to move north.
The responsibility of the first member state migrants arrive in must be complemented by EU cohesion.
The EU must also provide experts and funding to improve the behavior and management capacity of national asylum institutions.
This way, national decisions will be respected throughout the Schengen area, and the integrity of cross-border travel zones will be ensured.
After improving the behavior and management capacity of national asylum institutions, the asylum application processing can also be shared among member states.
The EU should establish stronger cooperative relationships with source countries and transit countries.
These contacts are crucial for repatriating migrants who are lawfully barred from entering the EU.
To ensure cooperation, the EU should leverage all diplomatic tools, including development aid and investment funds, as well as plans in areas such as security, trade, energy, agriculture, fisheries, climate action, aviation, and health.
The EU's migration targets, as well as skill cooperation to prepare for European job opportunities, can benefit third countries seeking stable remittances.
At the same time, the EU must address the root causes of migration.
This includes the population explosion in sub-Saharan Africa; climate change affecting food security; outbreaks of infectious diseases; ethnic conflicts; and a shortage of job opportunities.
The EU's assistance should focus on rebuilding stability and reducing risks by supporting security, community resilience, and good governance.
Success in this area would make investments more secure, unlock private and domestic finance, and achieve national economic growth, job creation, and provide alternatives to migration.
The new European Commission has the opportunity to move the EU away from its unconscious reaction to the migration crisis, towards a more consistent and sustained approach, whether internally or externally.
We must not miss this opportunity.
